    <div class="caption-accounts">Tag: none needed</div>
  </div>
  <div class="slide bg-charcoal divider-page" data-document-role="page" data-label="— Carousel 03 —">
    <div class="divider-num">03</div>
    <div class="divider-title">Calm Kids Don&#x27;t Happen by Accident</div>
  </div>
  <div class="slide bg-charcoal" data-document-role="page" data-label="C03 · Hook">
    <div class="counter">1/10</div>
    <div class="safe safe-top">
      <div class="accent-bar"></div>
      <h1 class="headline hook">Calm kids don't happen by <span class="script-word">accident</span></h1>
      <p class="body">Especially the ones who feel everything.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="slide bg-offwhite" data-document-role="page" data-label="C03 · Transition">
    <div class="counter">2/10</div>
    <div class="safe">
      <h2 class="headline h-slide">You can't talk a sensitive child into calm</h2>
      <hr class="divider-dotted">
      <p class="body">But you can build a world that helps them get there. Here's how.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="slide bg-charcoal" data-document-role="page" data-label="C03 · Tease 1">
    <div class="counter">3/10</div>
    <div class="safe">
      <h2 class="headline h-slide">Their calm <span class="swipe-yellow">borrows from yours</span> first</h2>
      <p class="body">A child's nervous system reads the nearest grown-up.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="slide bg-pink" data-document-role="page" data-label="C03 · Tease 2">
    <div class="counter-dark">4/10</div>
    <div class="safe">
      <h2 class="headline h-slide">Less noise, less stuff</h2>
      <p class="body">A busy room is a loud room to a sensitive kid. Fewer choices help too.</p>
      <div class="callout">you&#x27;re not spoiling them. you&#x27;re steadying them.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="slide bg-offwhite" data-document-role="page" data-label="C03 · Tease 3">
    <div class="counter">5/10</div>
    <div class="safe">
      <h2 class="headline h-slide">The same rhythm every day</h2>
      <p class="body">Knowing what comes next lowers the fear of what's coming.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="slide bg-charcoal" data-document-role="page" data-label="C03 · Tease 4">
    <div class="counter">6/10</div>
    <div class="safe">
      <h2 class="headline h-slide">One <span class="swipe-yellow">safe spot</span></h2>
      <p class="body">A corner, a tent, a beanbag. A place their body learns means “you can rest here.”</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="slide bg-offwhite" data-document-role="page" data-label="C03 · Tease 5">
    <div class="counter">7/10</div>
    <div class="safe">
      <h2 class="headline h-slide">Downtime after big days</h2>
      <p class="body">School, parties, and errands all need a soft landing after.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="slide bg-yellow" data-document-role="page" data-label="C03 · Climax 1">
    <div class="counter">8/10</div>
    <div class="safe">
      <h2 class="headline hook" style="font-size:74px;">A calm child is rarely about the child alone. It's about the world we build around them.</h2>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="slide bg-charcoal" data-document-role="page" data-label="C03 · Climax 2">
    <div class="counter">9/10</div>
    <div class="safe">
      <h2 class="headline hook" style="font-size:74px;">Lowering the noise isn't spoiling. You're teaching their body that it is safe.</h2>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="slide bg-charcoal" data-document-role="page" data-label="C03 · Action">
    <div class="counter">10/10</div>
    <div class="safe">
      <h2 class="headline h-slide">Comment <span class="highlight-yellow">CALM</span> and I'll send you my free Highly Sensitive Child Starter Guide.</h2>
      <p class="body">Save this one.</p>
      <p class="creds" style="margin-top:48px;color:var(--light-muted);">Speech Pathologist + Highly Sensitive Person + Homeschooling Mom of 4</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="slide caption-page" data-document-role="page" data-label="C03 · Caption (copy/paste)">
    <div class="caption-flag">Caption — not for posting</div>
    <div class="caption-body">Calm kids don&#x27;t happen by accident, especially the ones who feel everything.

Their calm borrows from yours first. Then it&#x27;s less noise, the same rhythm each day, one safe spot, and real downtime after big days.

A calm child is rarely about the child alone. It&#x27;s about the world we build around them. Lowering the noise isn&#x27;t spoiling them. It&#x27;s teaching their body it&#x27;s safe.

